{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475131"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:29:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:29:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12532"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12532"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.24,0.3,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77740"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5031"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63256"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44134"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77740"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6 day old male, born at term with no complications, presents to the emergency department following two days of difficulty breathing when feeding and decreased quantity of feeds. He has been vomiting between feeds and has had less wet nappies. On examination, the baby is grey in colour with mottled skin and femoral pulses are absent. Observations are as follows: systolic blood pressure 60mmHg, heart rate 175bpm, respiratory rate 56 breaths/min, oxygen saturation 60%. A VBG is performed and lactate is 12.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prostaglandin (prostin)","IV benzylpenicillin/gentamicin","Urgent surgery","Frusemide","Fluid restriction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant has a previously unrecognised coarctation of the aorta as suggested by absent femoral pulses. Their presentation at day 6 is important as the ductus arteriosus closes between 4-10 days post birth. While the ductus arteriosus was patent, the baby\u0027s lower extremities and abdominal organs had been perfused with desaturated blood and symptoms had been vague: decreased feeding, associated shortness of breath and vomiting due to poor gut perfusion. The closure of the ductus arteriosus immediately precipitates this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstaglandin (prostin)\u003C/strong\u003E infusion should be started as early as possible in infants with suspected coarctation of the aorta in order to maintain the patency of the ductus arteriosus. The ductus arteriosus connects the aorta to the pulmonary artery and \u003Cem\u003Efunctionally (but not anatomically) \u003C/em\u003Ecloses by day 3 of life, hence why it can still be reopened even at day 6. Blood flow to the descending aorta in severe coarctation is dependent on a patent ductus arteriosus therefore the closure of the ductus arteriosus leads to decreased systemic blood flow and cardiac failure. Maintaining ductal patency can be lifesaving and prostaglandin infusion should not be delayed while awaiting further tests or specialist advice. It is important to note that prostaglandin infusion can cause apnoea and hypotension at high doses so careful monitoring is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV benzylpenicillin and gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E is important to commence as sepsis should be concurrently suspected in a shocked infant. Despite this, it is not the most important next step in management of this infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgery\u003C/strong\u003E may be needed for this infant following discussion with the specialist however prostaglandin infusion is critical prior to surgery. Surgery is usually considered once metabolic acidosis has settled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrusemide \u003C/strong\u003Eis sometimes necessary in heart failure to improve urine output, in addition to fluid restriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is routine preoperative care for infants with coarctation of the aorta. This should be considered following the commencement of a prostaglandin infusion. The total volume of fluid depends on the postnatal age of the infant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prostaglandin infusion should be started as soon as possible in all infants with suspected coarctation of the aorta","Signs and symptoms of congenital heart disease may be vague immediately after birth, especially in duct dependent lesions","Prostaglandin infusion can cause apnoea and hypotension"],"references":["Singh Y. Diagnosis and management of critical congenital heart defects in infants. Paediatrics and child health. 2022;32(9):332\u20138. Available from: https://www.paediatricsandchildhealthjournal.co.uk/article/S1751-7222(22)00103-2/abstract","Ungerleider RM, Meliones JN, McMillan KN, Cooper DS, Jacobs JP. Critical heart disease in infants and children. Elsevier; 2018.","Child and Adolescent Health Service (CAHS) WA. Cardiac: Corarctation of the Aorta (CoA) and Interrupted Aortic Arch (IAA) Pre-Operative Management. [Internet]. CAHS WA Neonatology, 2020. Accessed 8 Jan 2025. Available from: https://www.cahs.health.wa.gov.au/~/media/HSPs/CAHS/Documents/Health-Professionals/Neonatology-guidelines/Cardiac-Coarctation-of-the-Aorta-CoA-and-Interupted-Aortic-Arch-IAA-Preoperative-Management.pdf?thn=0","Krishna MR, Kumar RK. Diagnosis and Management of Critical Congenital Heart Diseases in the Newborn. Indian J Pediatr. 2020 May;87(5):365-371. doi: 10.1007/s12098-019-03163-4. Epub 2020 Jan 28. PMID: 31989462. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31989462/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63256"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12532"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63256"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T08:50:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T08:50:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5031"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77740"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships"